(1972) Purchasers of printing presses to replace existing machines because of changes in design or to expand existing plants who were commercial printers engaged in "job printing" producing business forms, stationery, printed advertising, postcards, church bulletins, calendars, etc., were manufacturers within meaning of subdivisions (3) and (4) of subsection 2 of this section and therefore purchases were exempt from the tax. Heidelberg Cent., Inc. v. Director of Dep't of Revenue, 476 S.W.2d 502 (Mo.).

(1976) Held that conversion of a live hog into marketable portions of food is "manufacturing" within the meaning of this section. Wilson Co., Inc. v. Department of Revenue, 531 S.W.2d 752 (Mo.).

(1982) Advertising supplement which is printed solely to be inserted into newspaper and, in fact, is distributed in newspapers is integral part of newspaper from time it is printed and is entitled to exemption from sales tax. Daily Record Co. v. James, 629 S.W.2d 348 (Mo.).

(1987) Additive called Rolfite which public utility interjected into the combustion process in its electrical generating plant is fuel exempt from use tax by subdivision (1) of subsection 2 of this section. Missouri Pub. Serv. Co. v. Director of Revenue, 733 S.W.2d 448 (Mo. banc).

